subSection.paragraph:
Despite advances in the production of various enzymes by employing genetic engineering techniques, the preparation of some enzymes still relies on extraction from natural resources such as papain, ficain, bromelain, and peroxidase (POX), which are all of plant origin 
Sebasti´an et al., (2018)
. POX (EC.1.11.1.x) is a ubiquitous oxidoreductase with the ability to reduce one molecule of hydrogen peroxide to two molecules of water at the expense of oxidizing two reducing molecules (
Pandey et al., 2017
). This ability, in addition to its affinity for a broad spectrum of reducing species, has endowed POXs with the possibility of participating in vital physiological processes in various organisms and to find versatile applications in different industries (
Pandey et al., 2017
). An important subgroup of the POX superfamily belongs to Class III plant POXs (EC 1.11.1.7), which are extracellular enzymes 
(Jovanovic´et al., 2018
). Due to its accessibility, stability, and important applications, horseradish peroxidase (HRP) has already reached the market (
More, 2021
).

The large-scale preparation of HRP relies on horseradish cultivation, which is currently ongoing in several countries (
Spadiut and Herwig, 2013
). The global HRP market was valued at approximately 38 million USD in 2018, and it is anticipated to reach 73 million USD by the end of 2025, growing by approximately 8.5% annually during 2019–2025 (
More, 2021
). However, the seasonal availability of horseradish combined with low yields makes this method of HRP production problematic. In addition to the cultivation hassle, the current large-scale production of HRP offers mainly 
one type
of this enzyme (mainly HRP-C) (
Spadiut and Herwig, 2013
).

As the research proceeds, the POX applications have also expanded, ranging from the pulp, paper, textile, and polymer industries to immunoassays, analytical, bioanalytical and diagnostic kits as well as biosensor fabrication, wastewater treatment, etc. (
Enachi et al., 2018
). Concomitantly, the anticipated possible POX applications have increased the demand for miscellaneous POXs with diverse operational stabilities, substrate spectra, and pH tolerances. This trend has worked as the driving force behind the ongoing research on different POXs (
Krainer and Glieder, 2015
).

In contrast to the classical method of HRP production, some biotechnology-based methods, such as plant cell and hairy root culture, are bioreactor-dependent technologies (
Humer et al., 2020
). These approaches allow us to bypass the biological growth period of the plant as well as its agricultural difficulties. Therefore, the desired product is built up under controlled 
in vitro
conditions and harvested at the end of each subculture. Plant cell and tissue culture not only boosted the search for novel POXs but also improve the current knowledge about these important enzymes from both an applied and physiological point of view (
Kreis, 2019
; 
Krainer and Glieder, 2015
). In fact, studies on peanut (

Arachis hypogaea

) cell culture resulted in the first POX crystallography report (
Schuller et al., 1996
). There are still serious challenges ahead for plant cell culture to be used in cost-effective large-scale production plans (
Kreis, 2019
), however, advances in this field are promising (
Humer et al., 2020
).

POXalf
was purified to homogeneity, as verified by 
SDS
– 
PAGE
(
Fig. 2A
), through a 4-step procedure. The quantified results of this method are summarized in 
Table 1
. The salt precipitation step removed approximately 31% of the undesirable proteins from the raw extract, with a less than 10% loss of POX activity (
Table 1
). Although size exclusion chromatography (
Fig. 2B
) gave rise to a 3-fold purification, it was the cation-exchange chromatography on S-Sepharose (
Fig. 2C
) that resulted in 117-fold purification of 
POXalf
. The UV–visible spectrum of the purified enzyme (
Fig. 2D
) showed the characteristic absorption band of the haem group of plant class III-POXs (
Nnamchi et al., 2016
) with a Reinheitszah ratio (RZ = A402/A280) value of 0.57, close to the RZ value of soybean POXs (0.5) (
Parsiavash et al., 2021
), 

O. basilicum

(0.67) (
Mohammadnejad et al., 2021
), and tomato POX (0.7) (
Marangoni et al., 1989
).

